e, however, we always follow his work closely to make sure he is learning what he needs to learn and he is doing fairly well, but we still do a substantial amount of work with him that is encouragement based, which I know his teachers don't do. &#10;Our younger school is home schooled because that is what he wants, he does know that if he decides to go to school in the future he can, but we do have an agreement that he would have to start at the beginning of the school year. We would be more flexible with our oldest however, as he is in a school environment there is a risk of bullying, so if he was unhappy we would allow him to be home schooled, however it would be after trying to make the school tackle the problem appropriately. "/><type4:DocumentMetaData xmi:id="13" sofa="1" begin="0" end="1039" language="en" documentId="763" isLastSegment="false"/><types:WebArgumentMetadata xmi:id="24" sofa="1" begin="0" end="0" author="SamuelTaylor" date="07 January 2011 11:39am" docType="artcomment" origUrl="http://discussion.theguardian.com/comment-permalink/9050245" topic="homeschooling" thumbsUp="6" thumbsDown="0" origId="763" notes="" title="Why I home school my children"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="39" sofa="1" begin="0" end="243"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="43" sofa="1" begin="244" end="548"/><type6:Paragraph xmi:id="47" sofa="1" begin="549" end="1039"/><cas:View sofa="1" members="13 24 39 43 47"/></xmi:XMI>